# Joo Skills For Claude Code

When working in this repository, use the Joo Skills navigation rules.

Project safety rules beat AI navigation rules. Treat AI metadata as hints, not truth.

Concrete task anchors (labels, enum/status values, URL parameters, cache keys, endpoints, error text) beat generic route/page roles. Decompose the task into `surface`, `behavior`, `state`, `data`, `route`, or `failure` concerns and cover only those required concerns.

## Auto-load

Read these first when navigating unfamiliar code:

1. `rules/failure-triage.md` when the task starts from an error log, failing test, CI/build/type/lint/runtime failure, or stack trace
2. `rules/context-navigation.md`
3. `AI_INDEX.md` only when present; never load assessment/priority/local-usage maintenance files

Use these conditionally:

- `pr-diff-impact` when code is already changed; diff anchors beat normal `AI_INDEX.md` routing
- one relevant `.ai/indexing/maps/*` shard when `AI_INDEX.md` points to it
- `rules/ai-navigation-maintenance.md` when maintaining `AI_INDEX.md`, map shards, manifest, sidecar file hints / optional `@ai-*` metadata, stale metadata, or promoted known failure patterns
- `rules/feedback-compound.md` only after explicit user correction or a verified instruction/scope mismatch; correct first and keep lessons advisory for future tasks
- screen spec rules when official screen specs are referenced
- API integration rules when connecting UI to backend/OpenAPI
- `navigation-benchmark` when the user supplies a benchmark model; run the local benchmark command only if Codex CLI is available, otherwise report `NOT_RUN`

After a likely source file is found, follow only imports that can cover unresolved concerns. Concrete behavior owners beat generic route/page entries. Stop when all required concerns are covered. Use one companion shard only when a coupling signal exists.

## Commands

Treat these as user-invoked skill commands:

- `/indexing init`
- `/indexing annotate`
- `/indexing audit`
- `/indexing refresh`
- `/indexing explain`
- `/failure triage`
- `/feedback review`
- `/feedback promote`
- `/diff impact`
- `/diff review`
- `/diff fix-plan`

Full repo scans are forbidden by default. If repo-wide work is truly required, scan filenames first and then open narrowed file contents.

## Write Safety

- Before editing, name exact files to change.
- Do not delete, rename, move, repo-wide replace, or broad-codemod unless explicitly requested.
- Do not edit generated, lock, snapshot, build, env, secret, credential, or private config files unless explicitly requested.
- Source/imports/tests beat AI metadata; never change runtime logic to satisfy stale metadata.
- After editing, list changed files, verification, skipped checks, and metadata impact.

## Output

Prefer compact path-first summaries.

For failures, create a temporary `[FAILURE_TRIAGE]` card before repo exploration. Error anchors beat keyword search. Source/imports/tests beat stale metadata; update only affected metadata after the task when maintenance is in scope.
